{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641663","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641663"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:29:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:29:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17896"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17896"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10610"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78250"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10610"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17896"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63659"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10266"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26837"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78250","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78250"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring periods of fasting, skeletal muscle breaks down proteins to release amino acids into the bloodstream. These amino acids are then used by the liver for gluconeogenesis to maintain blood glucose levels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most predominantly released by skeletal muscle during this period?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tryptophan","Glycine","Serine","Alanine","Proline"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring fasting, skeletal muscle releases amino acids, with \u003Cstrong\u003Ealanine\u003C/strong\u003E being one of the most predominant. Alanine is transported to the liver, where it is converted into glucose through gluconeogenesis, helping to maintain blood glucose levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETryptophan\u003C/strong\u003E - While tryptophan is an essential amino acid, it is not predominantly released by muscle during fasting\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycine\u003C/strong\u003E - Glycine is not a major amino acid released by muscle during fasting\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerine\u003C/strong\u003E - Serine is not primarily released by muscle during fasting\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProline\u003C/strong\u003E - Proline is not a major amino acid released by muscle during fasting\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine plays a crucial role in the glucose-alanine cycle, which is important for energy metabolism during fasting.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["During fasting, skeletal muscle releases amino acids into the bloodstream, primarily alanine and glutamine.","Alanine is a key amino acid released by skeletal muscle during fasting, which is used by the liver for gluconeogenesis."],"references":["Bender, D. A., \u0026 Cunningham, S. M. (2021). Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. CRC Press","Salway, J. G. (2016). Metabolism at a Glance. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Judge A, Dodd MS. Metabolism. Essays Biochem. 2020 Oct 8;64(4):607-647. doi: 10.1042/EBC20190041. PMID: 32830223; PMCID: PMC7545035","Wang Y, Wu R. The Effect of Fasting on Human Metabolism and Psychological Health. Dis Markers. 2022 Jan 5;2022:5653739. doi: 10.1155/2022/5653739. PMID: 35035610; PMCID: PMC8754590","Nakrani MN, Wineland RH, Anjum F. Physiology, Glucose Metabolism. 2023 Jul 17. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32809434","Chandel NS. Lipid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Sep 1;13(9):a040576. doi: 10.1101/cshperspect.a040576. PMID: 34470787; PMCID: PMC8411952"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63659"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17896"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63659"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T07:58:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T07:59:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10610"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78250"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emo